g closely on individuals and probing deeply into their thinking and experience, the authors of these essays have discovered a wide range of reasons for why Chinese capitalists did or did not choose to live and work under communism. The contributors to this volume have all concentrated on the dilemma for capitalists in China's Communist revolution. But their approach to their subject through archival research and rigorous analysis may also serve as a guide for future thinking about a variety of other historical figures. This approach is well worth adopting to explain how any members of society (not only capitalists) have resolved comparable dilemmas in all revolutions-the ones in China, Russia, Vietnam, Cuba, or anywhere else.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aBusinesspeoplezChinavBiography. 0aBusinesspeoplezChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aEconomicszChinaxHistoryy20th century. 4aAsian Studies. 4aPolitical Theory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aChan, Kai Yiu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoble, Parks M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCochran, Sherman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCochran, Sherman, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGerth, Karl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHo, Tsai-man, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwan, Man Bun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKöll, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Pui-Tak, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeighton, Christopher R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSheehan, Brett, econtributor.